<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="2114" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,1545,1709]" box="[160,276,1545,1570]" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,1545,1570]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,1545,1709]" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">
This species differs from the other known species of this group in yellow body colour, the paramere protruding bearing three acute projections on distal one-third (
<figureCitation box="[1046,1155,1616,1640]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="18.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 10. Pseudostegana linyongi sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">Figure 10</figureCitation>
(c)), and the aedeagus distally strongly expanded dorsad, with strong basal process (
<figureCitation box="[166,277,1685,1709]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="18.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 10. Pseudostegana linyongi sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">Figure 10</figureCitation>
(b,c)). The 13.4% interspecific genetic distance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen and Toda" authorityYear="2005" box="[838,985,1684,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latifasciata">
<emphasis box="[838,985,1684,1709]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="2113">P. latifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" startId="18.[160,225,121,144]">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1160,120,202]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,264,121,144]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gong &amp; Chen, 2018" authorityName="Gong &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2018" box="[273,500,120,143]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="linyongi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[273,500,120,143]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Pseudostegana linyongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[508,589,121,144]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,959,1019]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">
within this group; there are 11 diagnostic sites between 
<taxonomicName authority="Gong &amp; Chen, 2018" authorityName="Gong &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2018" box="[845,963,959,984]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="linyongi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[845,963,959,984]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">P. linyongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[976,1069,960,984]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chen and Toda" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latifasciata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">P. latifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[294,391,994,1018]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 2. Diagnostic nucleotide sites in the alignment of the COI sequences of the genus Pseudostegana. Numbers at the top show the positions of the sites in the COI alignment (656–684 bp in length). Shaded sites are diagnostic for each species. Dashes (−) indicate missing data." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="2115" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1155,1063,1469]" box="[160,294,1063,1088]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,1063,1088]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1155,1063,1469]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,377,1097,1122]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Male and female.</emphasis>
Head (
<figureCitation box="[468,563,1098,1122]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 4. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana bingxueae sp. nov.; (g–l) P. husaensis sp. nov.; (m–r) P. lingyongi sp. nov." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(m,p)): Ocellar triangle yellow, narrowly elongated to anterior margin of frons. Frons, pedicel, first flagellomere, face, gena yellow. Clypeus brownish yellow. Palpus yellow, broad, large in male, medially half as wide as long. black. Thorax (
<figureCitation box="[166,256,1202,1226]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 4. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana bingxueae sp. nov.; (g–l) P. husaensis sp. nov.; (m–r) P. lingyongi sp. nov." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(n,q)): Scutum nearly yellow, sublaterally with thin longitudinal stripes. Pleura yellow above, brownish below. Katepisternal setae two. Scutellum brownish yellow. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[1065,1155,1237,1261]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 4. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana bingxueae sp. nov.; (g–l) P. husaensis sp. nov.; (m–r) P. lingyongi sp. nov." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(o)): Medial band greyish. Legs: Yellow. Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[697,787,1272,1296]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 4. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana bingxueae sp. nov.; (g–l) P. husaensis sp. nov.; (m–r) P. lingyongi sp. nov." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(r)): All tergites and sternites nearly yellow. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[426,533,1306,1330]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="18.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 10. Pseudostegana linyongi sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Figure 10</figureCitation>
): Epandrium roundly protruding on ventral margin, with about 18 setae per side. Surstylus protruding on posteroventral corner. Cercus ventrally slightly protruding. Paramere: apical process bifurcated, with two long sensilla; lateral process with two small projections and with numerous sensilla on dorsal projection. Aedeagus apically strongly curved dorsad, with several thin finger-like projections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[160,1156,1513,1712]" box="[160,333,1513,1538]" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,333,1513,1538]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="2114">Measurements</emphasis>
</paragraph>
